description:
Two-time Red Bull Air Race world champion, Kirby Chambliss took Los Angeles Angels pitcher, C.J. Wilson, on an aerobatic flight at Flying Crown Ranch, Chambliss' property in Arizona. An avowed race fan and race car team owner himself, Wilson experienced firsthand the power and excitement of the Red Bull Air Race as a passenger in Chambliss' two-seater Edge 540 race plane. Chambliss, also a five-time US Aerobatic champion, showed Wilson all the elements of the Red Bull Air Race, with some additional aerobatic elements thrown in for good measure. While in the air, Chambliss tested Wilson's baseball knowledge, and ability to handle high G forces, by asking him questions while doing aerobatics.

Chambliss is preparing for the return of the Red Bull Air Race in 2014, which features an eight race series around the world, with two US stops - in Ft. Worth on September 6-7and Las Vegas on October 11-12. The season-opening race will be in Abu Dhabi on February 28-March 1.

description:
“Everyone knows what it’s like on the swing at the playground. You swing as hard as you can and jump off. We wanted to do the same, but on a much bigger scale.” Marco Waltenspiel Red Bull Skydiveteam

No playground is complete without a swing. There can barely be anyone who didn’t go on a swing as a child – and while they might seem like simple devices, they provide unforgettable first experiences of adrenaline racing through the veins. The first time most of us get the feeling of flying through the air is on a swing. That’s how the four members of the Red Bull Skydive Team remember it, anyway. After all the successful projects they have put on together, there was a wish to go back to their roots with a special stunt – and make for the possibly world’s longest swing. The Red Bull Skydive Team has come together with two hot-air balloons and 125 metres of rope for the Mega Swing project, which isn‘t just creating some spectacular images but also might be a record!

source: Wings for Life World Run 2014 Denver, Colorado, United States
title: News Cut - Night Running
description:
The Wings for Life World Run is a first of its kind global running race happening simultaneously on May 4, 2014 at 34 different locations in 32 different countries. Runners around the globe will participate in support of bringing awareness to spinal cord injury and helping to fund research to find a cure. 100% of registration fees go directly to research via the Wings for Life foundation.
Unlike any other race, this global event has no fixed distance or finish line and every runner around the world, from part-time joggers to top professional runners, will start at the exact same time, starting at 10 AM UTC (6 AM ET/3 AM PT). The finish line is in the form of a "catcher car" which starts 30 minutes after the runners leave the start line. Once the car passes a runner, that signals that they've reached their personal finish line and their race is over.
The three USA race locations are: Santa Clarita, Calif.; Sunrise, Fla.; and Denver, Col.

source: Red Bull BC One Camp 2016 Kiev, Ukraine
title: News Cut
description:
During 12-14 August at the art-zavod Platforma for the first time in Ukraine the large-scale event - Red Bull BC One Camp Ukraine – was held.

Red Bull BC One Camp Ukraine – the festival, which reflects the creative landscape of Ukrainian scene and incorporates other elements of Hip Hop, urban dance and creative expression, alongside breaking.

Ukrainian and World scene top representatives came together at Camp in Kyiv to show and tell more about Hip Hop culture and its directions.

Highly topical daily program of workshops, lectures and contests did not give even a minute for a break - every spectator could try his/her hand in dancing, street art and music, and learn more about breaking, hip-hop, popping and house.

In addition, to complete the day, evenings were full of spectacular dance contests, live performances and parties.

The final chord of the three-day hip-hop marathon has become exciting and spectacular national final among the best Ukrainian B-Boys - Red Bull BC One Ukraine Cypher

The atmosphere was as heated, as was the air of this beautiful summer evening, when judges Roxrite from the US, Menno from Holland, and Mounir from France had to determine Ukraine’s best B-Boy under the applause of 3000 spectators that had come out to Art-Zavod Platforma in Kiev tonight to watch Red Bull BC One Ukraine Cypher.

DJ Smirnoff on the wheels of steel provided the sound for the dancers, while MC Scream on the mic fired up the audience. In the final battle, crew mates Pluto and InTact of Ruffneck Attack Team had to battle it out. Ukrainian B-Boys are known for their energy, great technique and style and both finalists were at the top of their game.
With judges’ votes 2 to 1, Pluto was the winner of the night and will represent the Ukraine in Japan this year.

source: Red Bull King Of The Rock 2011 National Final - Bucharest, Romania
title: News Cut
description:
Eight players from Bucharest, Timisoara and Cluj Napoca got into the local qualifying finals in Romania for the big finals of the Red Bull King of the Rock.
Some of the best Romanian basketball players did their best to get the ticket to Alcatraz, but only one had the chance to take it. To train them better for “the Rock”, the local qualifying finals took place in a real prison, the Rahova Maximum Security Penitentiary. This was the first time when a real basketball competition took place in a real prison. Not to mention that a part of the cons had the chance to see the games from their cells’ windows…
Each game was hard and equilibrated, but in the end, the best won. Hristu Sapera (30 y.o) is the winner. He started to play basketball on the streets of US, but after coming back in Romania, he had also another dream to fulfil - going back in USA, where his basketball story started - as he wants to play again and even be the “king of the rock”.
“One-to-one basketball is the same think as live is. You either win, or you go home. You only have one chance - don't waste it.”, said Hristu after winning the Romanian qualifying stage for the Red Bull King of the Rock finals.

source: Extreme Sailing Series 2012 Muscat, Oman
title: News Cut Day 4
description:
Red Bull Skipper Hagara was boiling over with anger after the the jury handed the Austrian boat a penalty before the finishing line in the third race of the day – as Red Bull was headed for an easy win. “If you get called back twice at the start, even though the videos clearly show that there was no way that we over the line, then you just can’t win,“ said Hagara. The double Olympic gold medal winner did not want to comment on the penalty assessed – allegedly for blocking a direct competitor at the start in the fourth race. “I’m just too angry today.“ Reflecting how closely bunched the world’s best multihull syndicates of the era are, America’s Cup winner Alinghi (SUI) finished back in 7th place. Matt Adams (Red Bull Trimmer) said: “It is brutally hard. All the teams are pretty much event out there. I’m sure that we’ll have good fortune on our side this year. You just can't have the amount of bad luck we had at the 2011 season final in Singapore and now at the 2012 season opener."
Red Bull nevertheless was only one point away from winning a podium spot ahead of the final race of the day (double points awarded) and even had a chance for the overall victory. Yet an untimely material defect on a downwind start left the team behind in seventh place coming across the starting line and they finished the race in fifth. Tactician Steinacher said: "The gennaker jammed and we couldn't build up any speed. Everything went wrong today. We have to just write it off, move on and keep working."

The Red Bull catamaran will now be shipped directly to China. The second stop of the season will be on the Olympic sailing course at Qindao from April 17 to 20. The team Hagara/Steinacher/Matt Adams (UK)/Graeme Spence (AUS) will use the break in action to train on a backup boat in Europe.

source: Red Bull Rockets 2011 Gran Canaria, Spain
title: News Cut
description:
Gran Canaria (Canary Islands, Spain)

The show didn’t let anyone down. The ‘Red Bull Rockets’, hold at Las Salinas de Pozo Izquierdo, was packed with incredible manoeuvres from the 16 best riders in the world, but it was the Spanish ace Darío Ojeda who won the competition after executing an astonishing 11-meter jump.
An electronic meter – equipped with an innovative technology that follows and reproduces the movement in 3D and in real time –, calculated the height of each jump executed by the participants, whom during the whole competition had it placed in one of their arms. Thus, the decision about who was getting the main prize – there were three categories in total – did not depend on the judges. The meter, designed by epicsession.tv, registered the height of the jumps objectively.

As for the competition itself, there were six rounds and the riders where divided in two groups. In the ‘white’ group there were Bryan Pérez, Jonás Ceballos, Aleix Sanllehy, Klaas Voget, Marcilio Browne, Marcos Pérez, Víctor Fernández, and Yannick Anton. And the ‘black’ one included Danny Bruch, Darío Ojeda, Eleazar Alonso, Kai Lenny, John Skye, Philip Köster, Ricardo Campello and Robby Swift.

Ojeda was able to get away from the water more than anybody else in the ‘Jump’ category, while the second position was for Ricardo Campello, one of the riders who really challenged Ojeda. Philip Köster was third in the end.

The ‘Best Trick’ award was for German ace Philip Köster, thanks to a spectacular double forward that was very much applauded by the spectators.
Finally, the Venezuelan Ricardo Campello, apart from being second in the ‘Jump’ category, was also the winner of the consolation wipeout prize, also thanks to a double forward trick, with the sole difference to the one done by Köster that Campello didn’t finish it.

A great amount of windsurf lovers attended the ‘Red Bull Rockets’ competition, hold at the coast of the beautiful sea village of Santa Lucía. The spectators followed very closely the movements and manoeuvres of the best international riders.

source: Red Bull Romaniacs 2017 Sibiu, Romania
title: News Cut - Prologue
description:
Gomez rides in a league of his own and Andy Fazekas does it again

Sibiu, Romania, July 25th, 2017 – Compared to last year, the 2017 Red Bull Romaniacs prologue appeared “manageable” to most of the riders at first sight. It did not appear to have the same terrifying obstacles as before and was even considered more “flowy”, but it proved to be much harder. Prologue manager Andy Fazekas had designed an “unassuming”, friendly appearing race track. But he had thrown in some killer traps that kept getting the bikes stuck every meter or so. Once on the track many riders quickly got overwhelmed by exhaustion, begging spectators for water and even were reduced to tears in some cases. The only way to get through was to keep the momentum and find one of the extremely rare flowy lines. Out of the many sections, the “Carpathian Kiss” rocks section and the “Triple Black” tires were the most feared. And that was before the rain… In typical Red Bull Romaniacs fashion the heavens opened up during the finals of the prologue and it downpoured on the some of the Bronze class riders. It soaked the course and stepped up the technical challenges for the Silver and Gold class riders.

During the day, it became obvious how quickly the skill level of Extreme Enduro is rising. For example, in 2016 Jarvis was the only rider crossing the concrete barrier at the finish, everyone else taking the “chicken line”. In today's prologue the majority of Gold class opted for the concrete barrier instead of the “Triple Black” tires. Also, three years ago the common opinion, even amongst the top riders, was that the prologue podium is reserved for an elite 3-5 people. This has changed, today there are at least eight potentials who could exchange places up there.

Among them, one rider stood out today and appeared to be riding in a league of his own: Alfredo Gomez. By the 3rd lap Alfredo Gomez charged to the lead and from there just increased the gap, incredibly starting to lap top gold class riders in lap seven. Gomez slalomed his way through the other racers, in total harmony with his bike, almost gliding across the obstacles as if they weren't even there. Finishing with over a one minute lead ahead of Billy Bolt who came in 2nd. Gomez hardly broke a sweat after the race and said: “I am in a great moment and have a really good feeling with the bike - I am playing with the bike the whole time. I am happy to be able to choose 3rd starting position for tomorrow!”

Billy Bolt, who made some headlines by not finishing his first Red Bull Romaniacs and getting lost in the Romanian wilderness, was thrilled with his 2nd place at today`s prologue. Billy: “I am going in to this year with more knowledge and experience. My strategy is to pace myself to last the full four days.”

Jonny Walker, who finished 3rd, was bittersweet about the outcome, fearing that his starting position for Offroad Day 1 would spoil his plans to win the race. Jonny “I am a bit cheesed off because it is a big disadvantage to start first - with no tracks to follow. Ideally you want to start 3rd to win the race. But I`ll make the most of it - it is what it is.”
